    <note>Jia(3) Juzhen [28885] Reconstruction of the history of this lineage was complicated and a CHECK of Juzhen's funerary inscription will hopefully confirm the following: Juzheng's grandfather, Shouqian (or Yiqian) [28886] (q.v.) is identified in JS and Zhao ZZ (1567) as a Wu Zhou (沃州) resident. When Kafeng fell to the Mongols, Juzhen, still a lad, fled from Kaifeng to Huolu county, where he is grouped with the biographies of the famous Song dynasty Hedong Jia(3). Wu Zhou and Zhending Fu are contiguous prefectures and Pingji and Huolu counties are only one county apart. My guess is that Yiqing [28887], Juzhen's father (identified in Umehara as Yi), held office in Kaifeng at the end of Jin. At some time in the past, a member of the Huolu Jia(3) moved the short distance to Pingji, and that Juzhen (or more exact, his mother), returned to the ancestral home. Huolu XZ (1556), pp. 735-738. YS, 153.322-325. WDY, 3, pp. 1634-5.</note>
